    <button x="90" y="580" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="76" display="setup hoja">ca
setup</button>
    <button x="270" y="590" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="105">export-network</button>
    <button x="60" y="630" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="81" display="setup italy">ca
setup-map
setup-settlements
cleanup-duplicate-sites
reset-ticks</button>
    <plot x="1120" autoPlotX="true" yMax="10.0" autoPlotY="true" y="405" xMin="0.0" height="175" legend="false" xMax="10.0" yMin="0.0" width="230" display="plot 1">
      <setup></setup>
      <update></update>
      <pen interval="1.0" mode="0" display="default" color="-16777216" legend="true">
        <setup></setup>
        <update>plot count connections</update>
      </pen>
    </plot>
    <button x="175" y="650" height="40" disableUntilTicks="false" forever="false" kind="Observer" width="65" display="go once">go</button>
  </widgets>
  <info><![CDATA[# Spatial ERGM: Settlement Network Simulator

## WHAT IS IT?
This model simulates the formation of ancient settlement networks. Unlike standard models where agents move, here the **sites** are fixed and the **connections** between them evolve.

It uses an **Exponential Random Graph Model (ERGM)** logic. The simulation treats the network like a physical system seeking equilibrium. It "tosses" links between sites and keeps them only if they improve the "social and geographical fitness" of the network based on your slider settings.

## HOW IT WORKS
The simulation runs a **Metropolis-Hastings MCMC** algorithm. Every tick, it proposes hundreds of random "toggles" (adding or removing a link). A change is accepted if it matches the "rules" set by the parameters below. Over time, the network "settles" into a stable state that reflects the trade-offs between distance, site size, and social clustering.

---

## THE PARAMETERS

### 1. Structural Parameters (The "Social" Rules)
*   **ergm-edges-param ($\theta_{edges}$):** The baseline "cost" of a link. 
    *   *Effect:* Usually set to a negative value (e.g., -4.0). This prevents the map from being covered in links. If it is too high (close to 0), the network will explode into a solid block of lines.
*   **ergm-mutual-param ($\theta_{mutual}$):** Reciprocity. 
    *   *Effect:* Encourages two-way connections. If Site A links to Site B, Site B is more likely to link back to A.
*   **ergm-gwesp-param ($\theta_{gwesp}$):** Geometrically Weighted Edgewise Shared Partners (Clustering).
    *   *Effect:* "The friend of my friend is my friend." High positive values create dense local "triangles" or cliques.
*   **ergm-gwid-param ($\theta_{gwid}$):** Geometrically Weighted In-Degree (Hub Aversion).
    *   *Effect:* Controls the creation of "super-hubs." A negative value discourages one city from hogging all the connections on the map.

### 2. Covariate Parameters (The "Physical" Rules)
*   **ergm-size-param ($\theta_{size}$):** The importance of site area.
    *   *Effect:* Large settlements (based on the CSV data) are more "attractive." High values create a hierarchy where everyone tries to link to the biggest city.
*   **ergm-dist-param ($\theta_{dist}$):** The general penalty for distance.
    *   *Effect:* A negative value means long-distance links are "expensive." This forces the network to be more local.
*   **distance-decay-lambda ($\lambda$):** The "Distance Wall."
    *   *Effect:* Controls how fast the probability of a link drops as distance increases. A high lambda makes the network extremely local; a low lambda allows "Small World" bridges across the map.

### 3. Tuning Parameters
*   **ergm-decay ($\alpha$):** Diminishing returns.
    *   *Effect:* Controls how much "extra" benefit you get from the 2nd or 3rd triangle. **Lowering this (to 0.1 or 0.2) is the best way to prevent the model from "spiking" or crashing into degeneracy.**
*   **ergm-steps-per-tick:** How many mathematical "guesses" the model makes per step. Higher values reach equilibrium faster but slow down your computer.

---

## WHAT TO WATCH FOR: THE "PHASE TRANSITION"
In ERGMs, you may notice the link count suddenly spike vertically (reaching thousands of links in a few ticks). This is called **Degeneracy**. 

It happens when the "reward" for forming triangles (GWESP) outweighs the "cost" of creating a link (Edges). To stop a spike:
1.  Make **ergm-edges-param** more negative (increase the cost).
2.  Lower **ergm-decay** (diminish the reward for too many triangles).
3.  Lower **ergm-gwesp-param**.

## STRATEGIES FOR EXPERIMENTATION
*   **To see "Isolated Clumps":** Use high Distance Decay, high GWESP, and very negative Edges.
*   **To see a "Dendritic Tree":** Use high Size Importance, negative GWESP (to prevent triangles), and moderate Distance penalties.
*   **To see a "Giant Web":** Use low Distance Decay, low Lambda, and moderate Edges.

## CREDITS
Based on the modeling approach by **Brughmans, Keay & Earl (2014)**]]></info>
